is saying,
I should constantly be
challenging my assumptions.

36:38.997 --> 36:40.765 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, it's not the news media.

36:40.799 --> 36:46.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's partly the news media, but
it's really
the consumer as well, breaking
out of those

36:46.171 --> 36:47.138 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
bubbles.

36:47.172 --> 36:48.139 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Tam, you see
that challenge.

36:48.173 --> 36:49.240 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You're out there covering the
news every day.

36:49.274 --> 36:51.042 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH, National Public
Radio: Yes.

36:51.076 --> 36:54.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, and the actual fake news
is often the
news that confirms our biases,
that we want

36:54.245 --> 37:00.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to believe that it's too good --
as a news
consumer, it's too good to
check.

37:00.185 --> 37:04.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, as a member of the news
media, you put
one foot in front of the other,
and you just

37:04.823 --> 37:11.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
keep going and, you know,
reporting the numbers,
the CBO numbers, and the Bureau
of Labor Statistics

37:11.563 --> 37:14.065 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
